Donald Trump appeared alongside Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas in Bethlehem on Tuesday after meeting for about an hour.Making statements to the press after the meeting, both leaders began their remarks by mentioning the suspected terror attack carried out overnight in Manchester.Abbas, speaking first, condemned the "horrible terrorist attack that occurred in the city of Manchester."Trump said the people resposible for the attack were "evil losers in life.""I won't call them 'monsters,' because they would like that term." Trump said.Read: Trump, Israeli leaders pledge Middle East cooperationTrump called it "interesting" that the attack in the UK occurred as he and other Muslim and Arab leaders, including Abbas, were engaged in talks about fighting extremist violence."I am committed to trying to achieve a peace agreement between the Israelis and the Palestinians," he said. "I look forward to working with these leaders for lasting peace." Send Facebook Twitter Google+ Whatsapp Tumblr linkedin stumble Digg reddit Newsvine Permalink http://p.dw.com/p/2dP6zNo specifics were offered about any steps forward, but Trump said Abbas and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu had pledged to do everything they could to achieve peace. Trump added he was "truly hopeful that America can help Israel and Palestine forge peace. Abbas repeated Palestinian demands that Israel recognize a Palestinian state and cease settlement construction on occupied territory.Last week, Trump addressed 50 Arab and Muslim leaders and called on them to "honestly [confront] the crisis of Islamist extremism."Trump will remain in Israel for the remainder of the afternoon, traveling back to Jerusalem to visit the Yad Vashem Holocaust memorial. He will then travel to Rome for his scheduled meeting with Pope Francis on Wednesday. Send Facebook Twitter Google+ Whatsapp Tumblr linkedin stumble Digg reddit Newsvine Permalink http://p.dw.com/p/2dPCOmz/rt (AFP, AP)